    "texts": [
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Identification features",
            "shortText": "<p>As with all members of this family, the body has become greatly elongated and cylindrical. The first two pairs of legs bear nippers, the second pair being much the larger, the next two pairs of legs are entirely absent and the last three pairs are strongly clawed and splayed to grip the substratum. This species is characterized by having a forward-pointed spike on the top of the head and an elongate second pair of legs (gnathopod 2), with a long basal segment and elongate distally-widening hatchet-shaped hand. &nbsp;There is no ventral spine between the bases of the legs.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_1_91",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Adult size",
            "shortText": "<p>Up to about 15 mm, excluding antennae.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_2_92",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Distribution",
            "shortText": "<p><u>Global:</u> Very widespread species, which has been spread to some current sites via shipping. Found across Europe,&nbsp; S, America, Caribbean, Asia, Australia, New Zealand and southern Africa.</p><p><u>Local/Regional:</u> Mozambique to Namibia.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_3_93",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Biology",
            "shortText": "<p>Caprellid amphipods all cling to hydroids, bryozoans seaweeds and the like using the specially-adapted hind limbs and extend their elongate bodies out into the water, where they snatch any passing food item passing by. They may remain immobile for long periods waiting for prey, but when disturbed they canmove rapidly along like inchworms. They can be extremely abundant on floating structures, such as buoys, ships hulls. This species is sometimes also found in large numbers on the&nbsp; surgace of the reticulated starfish&nbsp; <i>Henricia ornata</i>, but the nature of this association is unknown.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_4_94",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Food / prey",
            "shortText": "<p>Caprellids are though to be omnivorous, feeding on any small invertebrates, larvae, or other items that float within reach.&nbsp; Some species also filter-feed using their antennae.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_5_95",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Reproduction",
            "shortText": "<p>Females bear paired ventral brood plates that form a marsupial chamber within which the eggs develop into fully formed juveniles.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_6_96",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Similar species",
            "shortText": "<p>There are over 200 species in the genus <i>Caprella</i> of which 8 occur in South Africa. Local species can mostly be recognized by presence of absence of a spike on the head, and by size and shape of the nippers (gnathopod 2).&nbsp;</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_7_97",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
